  "why": "The paper does not evaluate or demonstrate cross-model attack transferability. All experiments treat each DNN as the tested/target model (they generate transformations and ETIs per DNN and fine-tune each tested DNN with its own discovered ETIs). The paper does not describe crafting fault-inducing inputs against a surrogate model and reusing them on separate unseen target models, nor does it report results of applying ETIs found on one model to other models to measure transfer of failures.",
  "evidence": "Page 2, Introduction: \"We evaluate 8 real-world DNNs (trained using 4 large-scale datasets) with 9 popular testing objectives and prioritization metrics.\" (shows multiple models are evaluated individually). \n\nPage 6, Evaluation Setup (Transformations): \"For ImageNet DNNs, we generate 1944 perception-based transformations that can trigger mis-predictions on all of them. For other three DNNs trained on three different datasets, we also prepare 1944 perception-based transformations capable of triggering mis-predictions for each of them... In sum, for each DNN/dataset, we prepare 1988 different transformations and each transformation is associated with one EP of its tested DNN.\" (indicates transformations and EPs are prepared/associated per tested DNN; no surrogate-to-target reuse protocol is described). \n\nPage 8, RQ1.2 (Trapped Testing): \"We equip each testing pipeline with all 1,988 transformations prepared, and study how the number of detected EPs changes with the testing epochs (i.e., the epoch in Alg. 1). Following Def. 2, an EP is detected if mis-predictions are triggered by applying its corresponding transformation on DNN inputs.\" (describes per-pipeline, per-DNN experiments). \n\nPage 9, RQ2 (Fine-Tuning): \"we collect all ETIs generated during testing to fine-tune the tested DNNs. Surprisingly, all 8 ‘repaired’ DNNs become more fragile to ~30% of the transformations.\" (fine-tuning and evaluation are performed on the same tested DNNs rather than measuring whether ETIs transfer across models). \n\nNo section or quote in the paper describes creating ETIs on a surrogate model and applying them to separate unseen target models, nor is there an experiment measuring whether ETIs discovered on one model also trigger failures in other models (i.e., cross-model transferability is not demonstrated)."
